snippet.textDisplay:
3:30 lol. On the shadowban thing: please don't, it's against a lot of moral codes and formal laws. The thing is that shadowbanned users aren't told they are banned, hence they don't get the chance to respond or fight the ban. In fact, a trueshadowban cannot be removed by repealing. Of course that makes it easier for the site (the shadowbanned users literally can't complain), but it is against many laws (like EU and Canada laws) to not allow for a responce.
To sketch an extreme case: some mod start shadowbanning innocent users in certain topics (s)he doesn't like. Since it's a shadowban, there is no process, no defence, etc. Therefore, the innocent users will effectively be banned.
I've seen things like above happen on Reddit, where a mad mod in a small subreddit banned al lot of the users, letting the subreddit die (or at least crippling it). (It was a NSFW monstergirl subreddit, but the mod disagreed on where the 'furry' line is, banning a lot of users who posted 'furries' according to him.)
